My team has been using Eclipse 3.3 and noticed this issue.  We found a work around that allows you to add Test Cases in JUnit 4 into a Test Suite.  Here's how it works:

When using the Wizard to create a test case using JUnit 4, it outputs something like this:

public class Test1  {

	@Test
	public void testTest() {
		fail("Not yet implemented");

	}

}

In order to make the test case recognized by the JUnit Test Suite Wizard, simply add

"extends TestCase"

after "public class Test1"

It will look like this:

public class Test1 extends TestCase{

	@Test
	public void testTest() {
		fail("Not yet implemented");

	}

}

This will cause an error, but if you click on the lightbulb and tell it to import whatever it needs, everything should work fine.

