Problem:
If you have code that is using inline double declarations, hot code replace will sometimes use random double values after the code has been altered and saved.  It produces very unexpected behavior when debugging code, forcing you to restart your vm in order for the values to be correct.

Test Case:
public class TestHotSwapError {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new TestHotSwapError().runTest();
    }

    private void runTest() {
        System.out.println(0.01);
        System.out.println(0.02);
        System.out.println("Debug point here");
    }
}

Steps to reproduce:
Set a debug point at the specified line and run the class in debug mode.
Once the break point is hit, increment both double values by .01, save and continue to the breakpoint again.  It sometimes takes a couple repetitions of this cycle in order to reproduce.

I attempted to reproduce with only one double, eg:
    private void runTest() {
        System.out.println(0.01);
        System.out.println("Debug point here");
    }
However, it only seems to reproduce when a "significant" number of changes have been made.  I haven't yet been able to determine what is "significant".

Sample Output:
0.01
0.02
0.02
0.03
-2.353438322139964E-185
0.05
-8.679225993314595E209
0.06

